@bstrie Most of Daniel's criticisms that have been dismissed are of the "throw away M:N threading right now" variety. Please consider that we are simply not likely to abandon our work on M:N before we've even optimized it (no handle migration yet—at all!); we don't have enough information to know whether it's worth it. In fact, we have some evidence that it will improve performance relative to libnative, because of the fact that we win on apachebench versus a multithreaded libnative with `RUST_THREADS=1` libgreen.

Furthermore, other language communities have had great success with M:N threads; if you were to ask the GHC or Erlang designers whether we should abandon M:N threading right now, the answer would likely not be the same as what @thestinger is saying. (In fact, I know this to be the case for Erlang at least, because we have in fact asked Erlang people for their opinion on this issue!) Certainly I think we should abandon M:N threads if they don't provide improved performance relative to 1:1, but we don't know yet and I think saying "you don't listen to Daniel" because we don't drop them immediately is not fair to us.

Please also consider that the reason we have libnative at all is because of concerns from developers like Daniel who think that 1:1 is a better fit for their application (though Servo would certainly need some sort of 1:1 mode, or at least OS thread pinning, which is basically the same thing).

@alexcrichton: The `new` and `with_capacity` methods are among the only few not working in the freestanding use case. They're convenience methods, as a container supporting allocators will have a constructor taking an allocator instance. In a hash table, they also hide the inconvenience of needing to supply a seed. All of the hash table methods will wrap the general one taking an 128-bit seed, the initial capacity and an allocator instance.

Containers can and should support the freestanding use case, so if the freestanding use case is handled in a separate crate then that's where all the simple standard containers will be (vector, priority queue, circular buffer, unordered map/set, ordered map/set, ...).

This isn't specific to containers, but containers are simple so it's easy to think about how they fit into the design. It gets more complex when you have something like a JSON parser, as a JSON parser _can_ work without the runtime too.

@pnkfelix: Traits are part of the public API and are a name you need to import to make use of the methods. I think every trait needs to be clearly thought out and should have a clear usage in generic code. It is a backwards compatibility hazard to need extra traits whenever functionality becomes optional or becomes available in the freestanding crate.

Eventually, nearly all of the standard library would be defined in the freestanding crate. There's no reason we can't define all the containers there and JSON/XML parsers. If 1.0 declares an interface as stable but it's not in the freestanding crate, then it either needs to be dropped or the standard library replaced.

We may decide to make a feature like floating point optional in the future, and while a configuration flag will not change the public API, splitting it out into another crate would be an API break.

@thestinger hmm, I would have thought that a trait T2 that extends another trait T would be a perfectly sensible way to represent optional functionality.

But I am going to try to understand why this is bad.  Is the core of your complaint is inherent in your phrasing that the backwards-compatibility hazard arises "whenever functionality becomes optional": are you talking about the scenario where in version 1.0 of the standard library, we have a trait `X` providing methods `foo` and `bar`, and then if in version 1.1 we realize that `bar` should have been optional, we no longer have a good migration path to take `bar` off of `X` and put it onto another trait `X2 : X` ?  (Verus a hypothetical `cfg` based solution where we would add some particular attributes above `bar`, but leave it in `X`, in version 1.1?)

Or is it just that my original thinking about `trait T2 : T { /* optional functionalty */ }` is simply distasteful?  (It seems like that is the sort of sense of taste that led the Java designers to have dynamic `UnsupportedOperationException` on various `Iterator` methods, instead of having subinterfaces of `Iterator` that supported operations like `remove()`, which would be more in line with the sense of taste I espoused above...)

@thestinger: My idea was that any unimplemented lang item inside of a library would refer to an undefined symbol and be sorted out by rustc at link time, which means that runtime support can be provided by a separate library which only the executable itself imports

This would let you implement anything requiring allocation or failure inside of libprim without defining any functions that would be provided by the runtime

I dont see how splitting it up like this would add too much complexity if done right
